est of quotable bits of credo, the miniature Socratic dialogue of the 1927 story “The Passenger”8 concedes another rare peek into the essence of his ethos. “Life is more talented than we,” says the first character, the writer. “How can we compete with that goddess? Her works are untranslatable, indescribable.” Hence,

